x4freetext: The experiment was performed at the
TRIUMF laboratory using a 32 MeV 9Li beam delivered
by ISAC-II linac
4He gas chamber TUDA with the length of 1.5 m and gas
pressure of 650 Torr was used as a thick target.
The target is long enough to stop the beam before
reaching the detectors. A 20 mm diameter Kapton window
12 mu-m thick was used to separate the gas-filled
chamber from the high vacuum beam line.
The detection system consisted of three
telescopes each made of 50x50 mm2, 50 mu-m thick
silicon dE detector segmented into four quadrants and
a 50x50 mm2, 1500 mu-m thick single PAD silicon as
residual energy detector. One of the telescopes T1
was centered at theta(lab) = 0 deg, and telescope T2
was adjacent to T1 at approx. 1400 mm from Kapton
window. A third telescope T3 was positioned at about
600 mm from the Kapton window and angled at 45 deg
with respect to the beam axis. To reduce background
from beta particles, threshold in T1 and T2 detectors
was set to 5  and 4 MeV, respectively.
A microchannel plate detector was placed
upstream of the Kapton window to measure time of
flight.
The Thick Target Inverse Kinematic
technique was adopted. If the target is extended
enough and beam stops in front of detector, the
ToF measurement allows discrimination of elastic
scattering from other reaction events.
